text:
I love your honest take on passive income. It bothers me that so many people act as if you can make money with no effort. It takes A LOT of effort to build a business or any gig that can eventually run on its own. Even then, you still need to do maintenance. A massive advantage that is not usually talked about is having an audience. If you have an audience, it is easier to get some of these smaller projects off the ground. A lot of people fail because they try to sell an e-book with no audience. 

With my business where we create videos and photos for consumer brands, it is doing very well, but now I am focusing on building my Youtube channel so that I can build an audience and create products that align with my audience.

Being an entrepreneur or successfully self employed (even as a dancer/former interpreter, yours truly) requires stacking several different skills
-budgeting/financial literacy
-time management
-sitting with ones deficiencies and doing something about it 
-**the actual skill you want to get paid for**
-openness to being very wrong and receiving constructive criticism
-openness to meet people and ability to detect who‚Äôs for your growth and who isn‚Äôt
-courage and confidence to be new at something
-courage and confidence to problem solve problem after problem
-ability to see a solution or know it‚Äôs somewhere in your mind or in the mind of someone in your community

I feel a lot of people are wanting to get paid without having a skill stack like this... @Silicon Valley Girl talks a lot about this on her YouTube and her 1+ million subscribers.

text:
Watched it all. I agree and love your philisophy here. The one point of feedback is The title can be overpromising. I followed most, if not all of these tips, but maybe I‚Äôm just not a good entrepreneur and I can‚Äôt get any of my side hustles to takeoff after five to six years and ten on youtube. I think a more realistic route for me is to live below my means and choose a job I love and try to grow my salary, while seeking remote opportunities that allow for travel. 
I think a lot of social media hypes Tim Ferriss and all the success stories like ali but there‚Äôs a survivorship bias there. Not all of us are great entrepreneurs or great on YouTube. I‚Äôve put out over 1500 YouTube videos and started many hustles, but I still suck at it. I‚Äôm trying to improve. I haven‚Äôt given up. I‚Äôm patient. But I think the lesson is that sometimes the employee route may be a more viable one that still allows you to find your passion. Not saying that is easy either. It‚Äôs tough to find work you‚Äôre passionate about that pays well for many normal citizens. They often have to choose one or the other to compromise. But it‚Äôs a struggle worth overtaking
